Charadrius obscurus is a species of plover bird. 
The bird has a distinct brownish-grey plumage with a white forehead and a black and white banded neck. 
It has a small, stocky body with a short, pointed beak. 
The wings are broad and the tail is slightly rounded. 
Charadrius obscurus is commonly seen near the shoreline of freshwater and saline wetlands. 
It feeds on insects, crustaceans, and worms. 
This species is often found in small groups and has a distinctive, high-pitched call.
